<div itemprop="articleBody">
<h2>Tutorial 4. Re-calculating the Pattern after Individual Measurements. </h2>
<p></p>
<p><strong>Now it’s time to calculate our pattern anew. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_3/Tutorial%204_files/image002.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p>
<p><strong>I need to adjust the standard pattern </strong>that I measured after putting the mock-up on the dress-form. Now you know what the third ‘pattern’ column is about. </p>
<p><strong>I have also taken measurements off my client </strong>– they are written in the second column titled ‘client’. </p>
<p><strong>Let us work on the side seam of the corset front. </strong>Let’s look at the difference between the original pattern and the client’s measurements. </p>
<p><strong>Bust front measurement.&nbsp; </strong>My client’s measurement is 47cm and it is 47cm on the pattern, too. There is no difference so I write a zero in the table (column 4, line 1). </p>
<p><strong>Under-bust front measurement.&nbsp; </strong>My client’s 39cm corresponds to 38cm on the pattern, which means I need to expand the pattern by 0.5cm to get the required size. But this measurement is always somewhat relevant. In other words a difference of 0.5cm might’ve easily been a mistake, a small inaccuracy. In any case, I write +0.5cm in the table (column 4, line 2). </p>
<p>Despite this 0 and +0.5cm along the bust and under-bust lines I tend to think the location of the side seam is correct. <strong>The side seam will be exactly in the right place if I don’t add anything in those areas. </strong>This means I write a zero in lines 3, 4, 5 and 6 of column 4. </p>
<p><strong>Both bust middle measurements </strong>coincide; there are no alterations on the central piece of the corset. I write another zero (column 4, line 7). </p>
<p><strong>Clip measurement. </strong>There is a noticeable divergence here! </p>
<p><strong>- Clip from the middle of the bust to the scye:</strong></p>
<p>This measurement shows at what level the cup should connect to the body in the underarm area. Since the pattern measurement is a whole centimeter bigger (10cm against client’s 9cm), we can’t leave it as is – otherwise the cups will push into the client’s underarms and rub against the skin too much. This calls for some alteration! Luckily, we can test everything in practice with the help of the mock-up. </p>
<p>Let’s return to the distance between the middle of the bust and the scye: <strong>&nbsp;I mark -1cm on the mock-up.</strong> Now looking at the table I have noticed that the client’s side length measurement is also one centimeter smaller than on the pattern – therefore <strong>I need to reduce the side of the mock-up by 1cm.</strong> I mark this centimeter on the side seam. It’s logical to assume that the whole cup is going to be reduced by 1cm starting from a certain spot (we’ll determine it precisely a little later) and gradually passing onto the side piece. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_3/Tutorial%204_files/image004.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>Below is the cup piece that’s going to be altered. </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_3/Tutorial%204_files/image006.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>I shall start from a certain point and remove 1cm to re-shape the piece. I might even start from the centre of the cup. It all depends on the final shape you want to achieve. If you want to keep the top line really round, you should start from the centre of the cup. If you want to even out the top line and make it straighter, you can start from the very edge. I believe it makes sense to start from point 1 marked on the mock-up, i.e. about 5cm below the top line. </p>
<p><strong>What concerns other cup-related measurements, they depend on the model.</strong> We would have taken clip-to-corner and clip-to-the-middle-of-neckline measurements if we wanted to make a V-neck indentation. </p>
<p><strong>But our model is different and we shall refer to the look of the mock-up we have sewn! </strong>As you can tell, I don’t need to remove anything in the indentation area since the corset was originally meant to have a high cut there. We have already discussed the shape of the cups, too. <strong>So I write -1, 0, 0 in the table (column 4, line 7). </strong></p>
<p><strong>Side length measurement:</strong> we have decided to reduce the pattern by 1cm. I write -1cm in the table (column 4, line 8). </p>
<p><strong>Back length measurement: </strong>&nbsp;there are no alterations at the back, i.e. its length stays the same. I write a zero in the table (column 4, line 9). </p>
<p><strong>So this is all that concerns the side seam of the front. </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_3/Tutorial%204_files/image008.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>And now let’s take a look at the side seam of the back. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Bust front, under-bust front, bust middle and clip measurements are not taken into account in these calculations. </strong>I put dashes in the table (column 5, lines 1, 2, 7 and 8). </p>
<p><strong>Bust circumference: </strong>my client’s bust circumference is one centimeter bigger which means I need to add another 0.5cm to the pattern. I write +0.5cm in the table (column 5, line 3). </p>
<p><strong>Under-bust circumference: </strong>there are no changes here; I write a zero (column 5, line 4). </p>
<p><strong>Waist circumference: </strong>I need to remove 1cm. I write -1cm in the table (column 5, line 5). Frankly speaking I pulled the measuring tape rather tightly when taking this measurement off the client and this 2cm difference is the result of this tightening. In other words her actual measurement must be 66cm and not 64cm. So basically this centimeter has little importance unless you want to make the waistline really distinct. Let us account for the tightening in our calculations and see if the waistline looks nice enough when we start cutting the fabric. </p>
<p><strong>Stomach circumference: </strong>there are no alterations; I write a zero in the table (column 5, line 6). </p>
<p>I copy <strong>side length and back length measurements </strong>from column 4. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_3/Tutorial%204_files/image010.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>There are two values we need to work with. </strong></p>
<p><strong>The first value is 0.5cm that should be added along the bust line. </strong>I suggest you should add this 0.5cm in the area of princess seams at the back to give more space for shoulder-blades. I always try to use those princess seams when I need to add a small value like this. Why? It helps prevent the body from pushing over the edge of the corset in the shoulder-blade area. So I shift the edge of the back a little using the princess seam. I shall write a zero in the Adjusted Back Side Seam column and 0.25cm in the Back Curve column to distribute this 0.5cm between the two princess seams at the back. I write a zero in the under-bust line. </p>
<p><strong>The second value is 1cm that should be removed at the waistline level. </strong>Okay, I am going to opt for strong tightening. <strong>And I have the following idea: </strong>I will remove a half of this value (0.5cm) using the front side seam. So I write -0.5cm for the waist circumference (line 5) in the Front Side Seam column. I will account for the remaining 0.5cm in the adjusted side seam at the back. I write -0.5cm in line 5 of column 6. Here we go, that centimeter at the waistline level has been removed. I’m not going to alter the princess seams. </p>
<p><strong>If we look at the side pieces of the front and back, </strong>I am going to remove 0.5cm at the waistline level. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_3/Tutorial%204_files/image012.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>Our calculations were quite simple. </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_3/Tutorial%204_files/image014.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>But I would like to point it out again that you are going to have to work on the shape of the cups and slightly reduce the clip-to-the-scye measurement. </p>
<p><strong>Of course you will have questions if you start altering the cups radically. </strong>All bodies and all breasts are different. I can only tell you one thing: you will certainly need to do some modelling with a cup shape like this. These cups are sophisticated and if you want to change their size, keep in mind that they have two princess seams and three separate parts. </p>
<p><strong>There is only one way of doing it: work on the shape, sew a mock-up and draw any necessary alterations right on it. </strong>For example if you need to make the cups larger, expand them towards the sides. Next you should add this extra value to the cups and cut them out of the body anew. It is then compulsory to sew a new mock-up and measure it again. This is some really meticulous work.</p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_3/Tutorial%204_files/image016.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>I’d like to mention that altering the cups of this corset might be challenging although you shouldn’t have any problems with adjusting its body after individual client measurements. </p>
<p><strong>I suggest you do the following:</strong> assemble the cup, prolong its middle princess seam upwards, re-draw the top line,&nbsp; cut the cup in half and apply all necessary alterations according to your client’s measurements the way I’ve described above (see the table). Afterwards you should re-model the cup trying to restore its original shape. It’s not that hard, you just need to invest some time and efforts into the process. When you’re experienced enough, you won’t need to cut the cup in half anymore since you will get the natural feel of how it should be. </p>
<p><strong>And again, the key rule: do not change the shape of the princess seam along which you have cut the cup in half! </strong>You should only ever work with the length of the cup if you need to make it smaller or bigger. And you may add a small value (literally just 1cm) towards the side of the corset body to expand the cup. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_3/Tutorial%204_files/image018.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>Remember that the distance between the side seam and the edge of the cup at the bust-line level should be about 5-6cm: </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_3/Tutorial%204_files/image019.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>Take this measurement directly off your client when you deal with a large size. </strong>Just ask her to lift her arm, look at the location of the side seam and feel for the edge of the bra. Mark that distance on the mock-up from the side seam to the edge of the cup. And then you will know how much to expand the cup if you start shifting the side seam. <strong>You should by no means alter the shape of the middle princess seam on the cups! Do not add or remove anything there! </strong>Otherwise your cups will resemble saucers. Even some 1-2mm might play a bad trick on you. Expand it upwards or towards the side, no other cup alterations are acceptable! </p>

</div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody -->
</div> <!-- Scope END: Article -->
